<font color="#FF0000">FINAL WORDS</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17 15:30:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
There should be no criticism for soldiers doing their jobs, ie killing people. For my part in the killing, I never have felt shame. It was kill or be killed. <br><br>
However, for the umpteenth time, not all that protested the war were communist sympathizers.<br><br>
I agree with you about searching the past while looking to the future.<br><br>
Read about John Paul Vann who was an adviser to the ARVNs in the early years. He was very anti communist and very much in favor of fighting them - with South Vietnamese - NOT AMERICANS - doing the fighting. It became evident to him that Diem considered ARVN as his personal security force to ward off an attempted coup, rather than a force to fight communists.<br><br>
Vann saw the quagmire America would be sucked into and warned against it, not only did he warn his immediate superiors, he briefed hundreds of officers when he returned from Vietnam. Within hours of a scheduled briefing of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, the meeting was cancelled. They didn't want to hear the truth. Vann, in 1962-3, was considered the most successful officer in Vietnam.<br><br>
Vann felt that the artillery and airstrikes which were called in on Vietnamese villages - many times killing large numbers of civilians - were unnecessary AND drove the ordinary peasant from our sphere of influence. <br><br>
Do some simple arithmetic. A conservative estimate of Vietnamese war dead is around 2 million. Divide that by 120 months which represents 10 years of active US involvement. Somewhere around 16,000 Vietnamese died every month. Many say we should have bombed the shit out of them. I maintain that we already were! That arithmetic alone was reason enough for people, from ALL political spectrums, to protest our involvement in Vietnam.<br><br>
By all means Cook, continue your bellicose crusade to &quot;expose&quot; those whom you blame for the fiasco in Vietnam. If you make an honest effort, the roads you take will ultimately take you to the ticketpunchers in Washington DC who saw the war as an opportunity for promotion.<br><br>
Ed Ramon,<br><br>
I told you in a private email a few weeks ago that I consider helicopter pilots &quot;the bravest of the brave&quot;. That still goes. Same same 60 gunners. I was there and that is how I see it.<br><br>
To the rest of you,<br><br>
I'm going to Vietnam next April. I plan to be in DC for Veterans Day happenings. Between now and November, I plan to do alot of reading about the Vietnam War in preparation for a book I plan to write. Good luck to all - and may you all find PEACE.<br><br>
wingman
